Deep Learning, Pretrained Model¶

  • Anita Taucher (agt4vw)

In this Notebook, I use RoBERTa to perform a Sentiment Analysis (Positive, Neutral, or Negative) on article headlines and article text. This model was pretrained by the the Meta Research team. It shows:

  1. The use of a Pretrained Deep Learning Model
  2. Exploring a novel dataset, which is comprised of 2,011 headlines and the first ~475 words from the latest news stories between 11 June 2022 and 6 August 2022, labeled with on a Bias scale: Left > Left Leaning > Center > Right Leaning > Right.

I obtain the pretrained model from huggingface https://huggingface.co/cardiffnlp/twitter-roberta-base-sentiment

This model rates sentiment using labels: 0 -> Negative; 1 -> Neutral; 2 -> Positive

To instantiate the model, I use the following from the huggingface documentation:

AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained()

AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained()

Example documentation is located at https://huggingface.co/cardiffnlp/twitter-roberta-base-sentiment

Get Data Files from Github¶

Because the data was collected in every-other-day intervals over a period of 9 weeks, there are several data files. Here, the data is loaded directly from the github repo.

In [ ]:
## Establish github connection
import pandas as pd
from github import Github

g = Github("MASKED_VALUE")
u = g.get_user("anita-uva")

repo = g.get_repo("anita-uva/ClassifyMediaBias", lazy=False)

## Loop through files in our github "data" directory

## First, get the file names from github data directory
data_files = repo.get_contents("data")

## Get ready to create a list of dataframes
dfs = []
df = pd.DataFrame()

## For each file in our data directory create a dataframe
## Add the dataframe to a list of dataframes
for aFile in data_files:
  if aFile.path.endswith('withbias.csv'):

    file_contents = pd.read_csv(aFile.download_url, usecols=['Title',	'Link',	'Description',	'Pub_Date',	'Publication',	'Bias'])
    dfs.append(file_contents)

## Concatenate our list of dataframes into one
articles = pd.concat(dfs, ignore_index = True).drop_duplicates().dropna(subset=['Bias']).reset_index().drop('index', axis=1)

Drop Unnecessary Data¶

Even though allsides.com provides article classification for Mixed and Not Rated articles, there are not enough of these types to contribute to our goals. As a result we drop articles with Bias ratings of "Mixed" and "Not Rated". We additionally set our Bias scale as an ordered categorical variable and properly type the Dates.

In [ ]:
## let's get rid of these guys, there's just not enough, and they're potentially confusing
articles = articles.drop(articles.index[articles['Bias'] == 'Mixed'])
articles = articles.drop(articles.index[articles['Bias'] == 'Not Rated'])

articles.Bias = pd.Categorical(articles.Bias, ordered=True, categories=['Left', 'Lean Left', 'Center', 'Lean Right', 'Right'])
articles.Pub_Date = pd.to_datetime(articles.Pub_Date)

print('Article Date Range')
display(min(articles.reset_index().Pub_Date.dt.date.unique()))
display(max(articles.reset_index().Pub_Date.dt.date.unique()))

print('\nArticle Bias Range')
display(articles.Bias.unique())

print('\nTotal Number of Articles')
display(len(articles))

print('\nAverage Length of the Article Description in Characters')
import numpy as np
np.mean([len(articles.Description.values[x]) for x in range(0,len(articles))]).round(2)

Prepare for Analysis¶

The Sentiment Analysis will provide 6 total scores for each article:

  • Negative
  • Neutral

  • Positive

  • Negative Percent

  • Neutral Percent
  • Positive Percent

We perform the Sentiment Analysis separately on Headlines and on Article Descriptions (the first ~475 characters of the article).

We create a headline (hl) dataframe and an article description (ad) dataframe. To those dataframes, we add all 6 scores for each article, so that our headline and article dataframes will hold all 6 scores for each article.

In [ ]:
## These are the new statistics we will add to the dataframe
## to add a new field, just add it to this list and it will be
## propagated throughout...

new_stats = ['negative', 'neutral', 'positive', 'negative_pct', 'neutral_pct', 'positive_pct']

Create the Headline Dataframe

In [ ]:
## Set Up Headlines df, the df name is HL not H one
hl = articles[['Title', 'Pub_Date', 'Publication', 'Bias']].copy()

## Add new fields to the df to be calculated in the text analysis
for new_stat in new_stats:
  hl[new_stat] = hl.apply(lambda r: 0.0)

RoBERTa Sentiment Analysis¶

In [ ]:
from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSequenceClassification
from scipy.special import softmax
In [ ]:
# load model and tokenizer

## This pretrained model determines Labels: 0 -> Negative; 1 -> Neutral; 2 -> Positive
## https://huggingface.co/cardiffnlp/twitter-roberta-base-sentiment

roberta = "cardiffnlp/twitter-roberta-base-sentiment"


## AutoModelForSequenceClassification is a generic model class that will be instantiated
## as one of the sequence classification model classes of the library when created with
## the AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(pretrained_model_name_or_path) class method.
model = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(roberta)
tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(roberta)

labels = ['Negative', 'Neutral', 'Positive']

Sentiment Analysis on Headlines

In [ ]:
## Sentiment Analysis on Headlines
for index, row in hl.iterrows():
  headline = getattr(row, "Title")

  headline_words = []

  for word in headline.split(' '):

      if word.startswith('http'):
          word = "http"
      headline_words.append(word)

  headline_proc = " ".join(headline_words)
  #print(headline_proc)

  encoded_headline = tokenizer(headline_proc, return_tensors='pt')
  #print(encoded_headline)

  # sentiment analysis
  output = model(encoded_headline['input_ids'], encoded_headline['attention_mask'])
  #output = model(**encoded_headline)

  scores = output[0][0].detach().numpy()
  hl.loc[index, ['negative']]  = scores[0]
  hl.loc[index, ['neutral']]   = scores[1]
  hl.loc[index, ['positive']]  = scores[2]
  #print(scores)

  scores = softmax(scores)
  hl.loc[index, ['negative_pct']] = scores[0]
  hl.loc[index, ['neutral_pct']]  = scores[1]
  hl.loc[index, ['positive_pct']] = scores[2]
  #print(scores)

  # for i in range(len(scores)):

  #   l = labels[i]
  #   s = scores[i]
  #   print(l,s)

Assess the Seniment Results¶

Sentiment across the Dataset for Headlines and Articles¶

Sentiment is not significantly different when considered across the full bias scale.

We see positivity is consistently the lowest sentiment, regardless of bias. And while it ranks much higher than positivity, negativity is always the second highest sentiment. Surprisingly, neutral is always the highest ranking sentiment for every bias.

When comparing headlines and articles, we see that positive sentiment for headlines is always ranked below 10%, whereas articles exhibit more positivity (over 10% in every case) within the article text. It seems that headlines may be less positive than the article content.

Articles classified as "Center" bias show less negativity in their headines and their article content. Maybe not surprisingly, the Left and Right extremes are more likely to exhibit negatvity in their headlines and articles than the more central classifications.

The "Left" bias shows the most negatvity of any classification in both headlines and article text. Center bias is narrowly the most likely to show positivity when comapred to all other biases.

Headlines and Article Sentiment by Week¶

Weeks 27 and 28 exhibit the highest negativity of the 9 week dataset.

In [ ]:
## Sentiment by Week of Year.

def triple_bar_plot(df, timespan='week'):

  import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

  plt.figure(figsize=(20,5))
  myplot = df

  if timespan.lower() == 'week':
    myplot.Pub_Date = myplot.Pub_Date.dt.isocalendar().week
    rotation = 0
  if timespan.lower() == 'day':
    myplot.Pub_Date = myplot.Pub_Date.dt.date
    rotation = 90

  myplot = myplot.groupby('Pub_Date').agg('mean')

  N = len(myplot.reset_index().Pub_Date.unique())
  ind = np.arange(N)
  width = 0.25

  xvals =  myplot.negative_pct
  bar1 = plt.bar(ind, xvals, width, color = 'burlywood')

  yvals =  myplot.positive_pct
  bar2 = plt.bar(ind+width, yvals, width, color='darkorange')

  zvals =  myplot.neutral_pct
  bar3 = plt.bar(ind+width*2, zvals, width, color = 'bisque')

  plt.xlabel("{} of Year".format(timespan.title()))
  plt.ylabel('Sentiment Percent')

  plt.xticks(ind+width, myplot.reset_index().Pub_Date.unique(), rotation=rotation)
  plt.legend( (bar1, bar2, bar3), ('Negative', 'Positive', 'Neutral') )

  return plt

## Headline Plot
plt = triple_bar_plot(hl[['Pub_Date', 'negative_pct', 'positive_pct', 'neutral_pct']].copy())
plt.title("Headlines:  Mean Sentiment by Week")

## Article Text Plot
plt = triple_bar_plot(ad[['Pub_Date', 'negative_pct', 'positive_pct', 'neutral_pct']].copy())
plt.title("Article Text:  Mean Sentiment by Week")

plt.show()

Headlines and Article Sentiment by Day¶

The chart shows 11 June 2022 as one of the most negative news days, but it is significant to note the corpus for that day is made up of only 2 articles, and both describe the war in Ukraine. While that is exceedingly negative, that day does not have a balance of articles as other days in the dataset.

August 6, another negative news day included articles about the war in Ukraine and China's change in their US foreign policy, in retaliation to Speaker Nancy Pelosi's visit to Taiwan.

Other notable negative news days include 7/5 where news is characterized by extremely high oil prices, the mass shooting in Highland Park, Illinois, and a falling stock market; and 6/26 with news of demonstrations from the Supreme Court Decision overturning Roe vs Wade, high oil prices, and the war in Ukraine.

Negative, Positive, and Neutral Ratings by Bias by Week¶

A graph like this is good for showing exceptions to the average. We can clearly see the groupings of Negative, Positive, and Neutral bars. Any bars that exceed the thresholds of the others for their week can be investigated.

For example, the Left appears to be exceedingly negative on week 30. Looking into the news articles by the Left for that week, we see subjects such as Monkeypox, Covid, and the January 6th insurrection. The right bias was more likely to discuss the economy, with a mention of covid.
